<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-972-012  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 972 012.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Dec 1 1989 v28 n23 p84(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>True integration: the EDA challenge for the 1990s. (electronicdesign automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Friedmann, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Customers are putting increasing pressure on manufacturers tospeed up the time-to-market cycle.andP;  The product development cycleneeds to be shortened to relieve this pressure.andP;  Systemmanufacturers and electronic design automation (EDA) companies canachieve this goal together.andP;  Manufacturers can take a hard look atthe way they do things and change them.andP;  EDA firms need to supportthis effort with integrated design environments.andP;  New tools shouldfree designers from underlying logical details.andP;  Designers need towork at higher levels to manage the vast complexity and massiveamounts of data related to designs of the 1990s.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DesignAutomationIntegrated ApproachCustomer RelationsUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>